    category: "Science & Innovation",
    content: "In 1928, the Indian physicist Sir C.V. Raman discovered a phenomenon that revolutionized the study of light and matter. While studying the blue color of the Mediterranean Sea, Raman conducted experiments in Kolkata, demonstrating that when light passes through a transparent liquid, a small fraction of the scattered light changes wavelength.\n\nThis phenomenon, known as the Raman Effect, occurs because light photons exchange energy with the molecules of the medium. The discovery won Raman the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1930, making him the first Asian to win a Nobel Prize in science, and provided a powerful tool for chemical analysis.",
